<br>
The dining scene was a grand one. Lavish tapestries adorned sculpted stone walls and the marble floor glinted under sparkling chandeliers. The long table - ornately carved solid oak - was empty save for two seats.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have asked you here,&quot; he continued, his voice echoing throughout the hall, &quot;because I grow tired of the wars that plague our land. The forces of good grapple with the forces of evil, each side believing their victories are for a greater power. How deluded they are! For violence only serves to glorify the victor, to appeal to his senses of greed and power-lust.&quot; He paused a moment to let the echo die down. &quot;But here, this very night, I demand a better solution. My house can stand against the foolishness that is principle, the meaningless battles between good and evil. And we can triumph! Here tonight, I declare the House Avishot independent of any petty crusade of man. It shall live according to its own will!&quot;<br>
<br>
He walked to the end of the table, where two ambassadors - two great symbols of opposing forces - sat in disbelief.<br>
<br>
&quot;My dear friends,&quot; Vendarath said slowly, drawing out the syllables. &quot;It's a shame you travelled all the way from Neriak and Felwithe with such high hopes for peace - or did you think perhaps you could make a dramatic show of storming out and gain your ruler's favor?&quot;<br>
<br>
The Tier`Dal ambassador said furiously, &quot;You betray your own kind! This talk of independence is madness...&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, is it?&quot; replied Vendarath. &quot;On the contrary! The Queen may not tolerate dissension, but with her armies tied up in this useless war, she has no means to enforce her will.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your ignorance is absolute, as is your colleague's. So I will make this quick. If you would both be so kind as to finish your wine,&quot; - he paused while they drained their glasses - &quot;I will leave you to your own devices.&quot;<br>
<br>
The High Elven ambassador looked relieved. &quot;Then we can finally get on with the peace talks? Your tirade was interesting, Avishot, but you know very well it has nothing to do with either of us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Again, you misunderstand.&quot; Vendarath swirled his glass slowly and took a probing sip. &quot;It was only a precaution - sometimes the poison sinks to the bottom.&quot;<br>
<br>
Throwing the goblet to the floor, Vendarath de Avishot strode from the room, shouting a farewell to the ambassadors.<br>
<br>
